<p>The price gap has narrowed significantly. Green hosting no longer carries a heavy premium. Some providers even match or beat traditional hosts on price while delivering better performance.</p>
<h2>Is Green Hosting a Direct Google Ranking Factor?</h2>
<p>No. Google has never stated that hosting on renewable energy affects rankings directly. John Mueller addressed this in a 2023 office hours session. He confirmed that Google does not evaluate a site's carbon footprint as a ranking signal.</p>
<p>However, green hosting improves the factors Google does measure. These indirect effects are substantial.</p>
<h3>Server Response Time and TTFB</h3>
<p>Time to First Byte (TTFB) measures how quickly a server responds to a request. Google confirmed TTFB as part of the Core Web Vitals assessment. Green hosts running modern NVMe storage and optimized stacks typically deliver TTFB under 200 milliseconds. Legacy shared hosting often exceeds 800 milliseconds.</p>
<p>A study by <a href="https://backlinko.com/page-speed-stats">Backlinko</a> analyzed 5.2 million pages. Sites with TTFB under 200ms ranked significantly higher than those above 600ms. The correlation is clear. Faster servers rank better.</p>
<h3>Uptime and Crawl Budget</h3>
<p>Googlebot allocates a crawl budget to each site. If your server is down when Googlebot visits, that crawl attempt is wasted. Repeated downtime reduces how often Google crawls your site. This delays indexation of new content and updates.</p>
<p>Green hosts report average uptime of 99.97% or higher. Budget shared hosting often falls to 99.5%. That 0.47% difference equals roughly 41 hours of downtime per year. Every hour is a missed opportunity for Googlebot to index your content.</p>
<h3>Core Web Vitals Impact</h3>
<p><a href="/blog/improve-core-web-vitals/">Core Web Vitals</a> are confirmed ranking factors. Green hosting improves all three metrics.</p>
<p><strong>Largest Contentful Paint (LCP).</strong> Modern servers with SSD/NVMe storage and optimized caching deliver page content faster. Green hosts typically achieve LCP under 2.5 seconds. Budget hosts often exceed 4 seconds.</p>
<p><strong>First Input Delay (FID) / Interaction to Next Paint (INP).</strong> Efficient server-side rendering and faster resource loading reduce the time before a page becomes interactive. INP replaced FID in March 2024 and carries more weight.</p>
<p><strong>Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS).</strong> While CLS is primarily a front-end issue, slow-loading fonts and images from underpowered servers can trigger layout shifts. Fast, stable hosting reduces these delays.</p>
