<h2>FAQ</h2>
<p><strong>Is green hosting a direct Google ranking factor?</strong></p>
<p>No. Google has not confirmed sustainability as a ranking signal. However, green hosting improves Core Web Vitals, uptime, and server response time. These are confirmed ranking factors.</p>
<p><strong>How long does it take to see SEO results after switching to green hosting?</strong></p>
<p>Most sites see Core Web Vitals improvements within days. Organic traffic changes typically appear within 30-60 days, once Googlebot has recrawled the site.</p>
<p><strong>Does green hosting cost more than standard hosting?</strong></p>
<p>Not necessarily. Many green hosts price competitively with traditional providers. Shared green hosting ranges from $5-15 per month. The performance improvements often justify any small premium.</p>
<p><strong>Can I verify my host is actually green?</strong></p>
<p>Check the <a href="https://www.thegreenwebfoundation.org/directory/">Green Web Foundation directory</a>. They audit and verify claims. Avoid hosts that use vague terms like "eco-friendly" without third-party certification.</p>
<p><strong>Should I migrate my entire site at once or in phases?</strong></p>
<p>For most sites, a full migration is fine if you follow the checklist above. Large e-commerce sites with complex integrations should use a phased approach. Start with a staging environment, then migrate low-traffic sections first.</p>
<p><strong>What is the carbon footprint of a typical website?</strong></p>
<p>A standard web page produces approximately 0.5 grams of CO2 per view. An optimized site on green hosting can reduce this to 0.1 grams or less. A site with 100,000 monthly views would save approximately 480 kg of CO2 per year.</p>
<p><strong>Do green hosts support WordPress, Shopify, and other platforms?</strong></p>
<p>Yes. Most green hosts offer one-click WordPress installation, WooCommerce support, and compatibility with all major CMS platforms. Some also offer managed WordPress plans with automatic updates and backups.</p>
